result.execSummary:
The defendant Julian R. Blackshear was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver Heroin (<3g), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(d)1.
  • Manuf/Deliver Amphetamine(<=3g), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(e)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Julian R. Blackshear in court, in custody via video with attorney Stephen M Compton.  Zeke S Wiedenfeld appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Matter before the Court is set for competency.
Atty Compton makes record that Deft believes he is incompetent although the reports say he is competent. 
State is in compliance with Ch. 950, there are no victims present.
Deft informs the Court that he believes he is not competent to proceed.

State calls Dr. Jenna Niess, she appears via telephone. Dr. Niess, duly sworn & testifies on direct by DA Wiedenfeld.
Court will take judicial notice of Dr. Niess's report filed 11/5/2021 as evidence in this hearing.

11:11am Cross-Exam by Atty Compton

No re-direct.
Deft makes statement
Dr. Niess responds to Court's questions.

Nothing further for Dr. Niess, call is disconnected.
No further evidence from the parties.

DA Wiedenfeld makes record that the Court find the Deft competent to proceed.
Record by Atty Compton that Deft believes he is not competent to proceed & Atty Compton asks that the Court send Deft to Mendota or Winnebago.

Court makes record that the State bears the burden of proof, Deft claims to be incompetent. 
Court notes that Deft's unsworn testimony does not change the opinon of Dr. Niess's testimony. 
Court believes Deft is competent & able to assist in his cases including the revocation file.

Court notes that Deft is on a hold & would like to set trial dates. 
Files are not joined, misdemeanors will be back to back. 
State is not asking for speedy disposition.
Deft is not demanding speedy at this time but would like to speak with Atty Compton.

Court will set status at this time to address how to move forward.
